Al Baraka Banking, Deyaar, Dana Gas: Persian Gulf Equity Preview

-- B y   M o u r a d   H a r o u t u n i a n
-- 
2011-08-11T02:00:00Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-08-11/al-baraka-banking-deyaar-dana-gas-persian-gulf-equity-preview.html
 The following stocks may rise or
fall in Persian Gulf markets. Stock symbols are in parentheses
and prices are from the last close.  Dubai’s  DFM General Index (DFMGI)  rose 1.2 percent, the largest
gain in a month, to 1,460.96 and  Abu Dhabi ’s  ADX General Index (ADSMI) 
advanced 1 percent. Saudi Arabia’s market is closed for the
weekend today.  Albaraka Banking Group (BARKA)  BSC: The Turkish unit of
Bahrain’s biggest publicly traded Islamic lender,  Albaraka Turk
Katilim Bankasi AS (ALBRK) , plans to raise $240 million from a
syndicated Murabahah facility this quarter to be used for
expansion. The shares dropped 1.7 percent to $1.15, when they
last traded on Aug. 8.  Commercial Bank of Kuwait (CBK KK): The Kuwaiti lender’s
local and foreign-currency deposit ratings were affirmed at
A2/Prime-1 by Moody’s Investors Service, with a negative
outlook. The shares declined 2.3 percent to 850 fils, when they
last traded Aug. 9.  Dana Gas PJSC (DANA)  : The fuel producer with most of its
output coming from  Egypt  said second-quarter profit more than
tripled to 124 million dirhams ($34 million) from 33 million
dirhams a year earlier. The shares were unchanged at 55 fils.  Deyaar Development (DEYAAR)  PJSC: The property company
part-owned by  Dubai Islamic Bank PJSC (DIB)  returned to profit in the
first half. Net income was 44.4 million dirhams after a loss of
344 million dirhams a year earlier. Deyaar’s shares jumped 4.8
percent to 26.4 fils.  Kuwait Finance House (KFIN)  : The country’s largest
Islamic bank by assets expects to gain $40 million from a stake
sale by a unit. The unit expects to get approval for the stake
sale by the end of this month and the gain will be added to the
fourth-quarter results. The shares rose 1.1 percent to 900 fils.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Mourad Haroutunian in Riyadh at 
 mharoutunian@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
